<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title></title></head><body><div><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Submission to the Justice Select Committee on Transforming Rehabilitation</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Summary</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Statistics show that we can do better to reduce reoffending, particularly among ex-prisoners, but there is no crisis in our probation services.  </span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Reforms ought to be proportionate to the extent of problems and the opportunity for improvement.  </span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Transforming Rehabilitation is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">very </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">badly designed and contains inbuilt risks to the stability and quality of probation services into the longer-term.  </span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Instead, urgent attention should be given to better services for ex-prisoners while continuing reform to public sector probation.  PbR pilots should be extended to all prisoners sentenced to less than twelve months and public sector probation should be reformed through outcome-based contracts, mandatory commissioning of all functions except court work and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">development of trusts as expert commissioners.  </span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Transforming Rehabilitation is so unfit for purpose that the Justice Select Committee should continue to question its basic principles and premises and explore alternative options.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The context</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Government says (in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Transforming Rehabilitation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Ministry of Justice January 2013) that the system “is failing in one of its primary purposes…. to reduce reoffending</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">”</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It is particularly critical of the reconviction rate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> for those sentenced to less than 12 months in prison.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Government policy should be driven by evidence.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Publicly available material </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super">1,2,3</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">shows</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> that:</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Recorded crime has fallen internationally since 1995 including in England and Wales.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In 2005 – 2009 England and Wales had higher than average crime rates </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">internationally </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">but </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">also </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the fastest falling </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">international</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">crime rate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Reoffending (or</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> more precisely</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> reconviction) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in England and Wales </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rates </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">has fallen</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.1% </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">from</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> 2000 but </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">levell</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> off from 2006 onwards </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">increased</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> 0.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">6% </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in the year to June 2011</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The average number of reoffences per offender </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in England and Wales </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">has fallen</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">14.9% </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">from</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> 2000 but increased </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2.4% </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">year to June 2011</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Reoffending (or more precisely reconviction) rates </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in England and Wales </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">by people on community orders and suspended sentences (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">i.e.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> broadly speaking those supervised by the probation service) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">has fallen</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> 3.7% since 2000 but increased 0.2% in the year to June 2011</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The average number of reoffences per offender on community orders and suspended sentences </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in England and Wales </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">has fallen</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> 17% since 2000 but increased 2.6% in the year to June 2011</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The biggest increase in reoffending amongst adults </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in England and Wales </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">since 2000 was 3.9% in relation to those sentenced to less than 12 months in prison</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  These offenders received no statutory supervision.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The biggest reductions in reoffending amongst adults </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in England and Wales </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">since 2000 was 3.7% for those sentenced to 12 months to four years and 9.7% for those who </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">were sentenced to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> a community sentence</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  Both these groups were subject to statutory probation supervision.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Calculation methods for r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">econviction rates are too different </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">country to country </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to allow international comparisons to be made with any confidence</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> but tentatively it can be said that England and Wales falls within the “normal range” internationally</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> although </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">we</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> may be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">marginally</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> higher than </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the international </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">average</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">What </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">should</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> this </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">indicate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">principles that inform </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">national </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">policy</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">?</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">There </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">is no</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> crisis in our </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">national performance on reducing reoffending</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> but w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e should focussed on trying to improve performance</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> because we can do better</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.   </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">W</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">hile w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e ought to be able to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">improve</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">olicy should be proportionate to the scale of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the probably modest </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rather than spectacular </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">improvements </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the statistics suggest </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">it </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">would be</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">possible</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to achieve</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Probation supervision has a measurable </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">positive </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">effect on reoffending rates</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  We should not to destabilise this </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">but</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> tak</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> steps to increase its effectiveness</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">he primary </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">target for reducing reoffending further </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">should be those sentenced </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to less than 12 months in prison.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">How should we do this?</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Government has decided to adopt a radical approach</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> which is characterised by</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">weaknesses:</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Transforming Rehabilitation (TR) is an extraordinary over-reaction to what the evidence tells us is the situation.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  It involves the destruction of the whole current national system for assessing and supervising offenders and its replacement with an approach that does not seem to be evidence based.   The priority aim – to improve reoffending rates by those released from prison – can be achieved better through targeted action than by an undifferentiated attack on the entire system for supervising offenders: most offenders under statutory supervision are on community orders not post-release licences.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The new system will erode and complicate the essential close working links between probation and other local services, bodies and organisations</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 69.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Secretary of State wants a “closer alignment and integration” with Police and Crime Commissioners (PCCs) and local authority boundaries.  The proposals in this consultation would add nothing to, and probably weaken, current arrangements in which all probation trusts’ geographical “footprints” are the same as PCCs’ at area level and Local Authorities’ at local delivery (LDU) level. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 69.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Probation trusts are statutory “Responsible Authority” members of Community Safety Partnerships which have had, since 2010, a statutory duty to produce plans to reduce reoffending.  It is unclear how these responsibilities could be fulfilled under these proposals given that at least two-thirds of the work with local offenders would be carried out by bodies that would have no local accountability.   </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 68.33pt; padding-left:3.67pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In future there will be two probation services (the local representatives of the new NPS and the contracted provider) in every locality delivering similar services side by side and sometimes via one another.  Each will have to form working relationships with other local organisations, bodies and services for the delivery of the joint or complementary services which characterise effective local work with offenders</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The quality of work with offenders depends on staff with the right skills and attitudes but there are no plans for how staff delivering probation services will be trained in future.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  The new National Probation Service (NPS) will not be able to provide practice-based training because it will not have the capacity and it would not be appropriate for new trainees to work with the most serious offenders.  It is unclear who will provide the academic element of training.  The Government proposes a professional body or institute.  While this may be an excellent way to promote standards it is difficult to see how it could resolve the problem of how training is provided or of who has the authority to mandate the content of training. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The breaking up of probation will lead to the erosion of organisational knowledge about best practice in managing and rehabilitating offenders</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  While the proposed new institute will have a part to play it will not be able to replace the everyday workplace-based sharing of intelligence about good professional practice and the career development experience of today’s probation staff.  Over time employees of contracted services will lose experience in, for example, report-writing; residential work; victim issues; assessment and management of risk, breach and recall; MAPPA; and how courts and the Parole Board work while staff in the NPS will lose touch with unpaid work and the breadth of experience of supervising offenders with high needs but low risk such as petty recidivists.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Sharing the assessment of risk across two organisations builds</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">in weakness to public protection work.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  The most effective risk assessment is an unbroken process involving periodic “actuarial” and continuous “clinical” monitoring, review and action by a single responsible person.  The new arrangements make it impossible for this to happen in the contracted services.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Financial uncertainty</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  Contracts will be with lead providers who can bear the financial risks but it is not unknown for private sector companies providing public services to fail, financially or in terms of quality of service.  With a much reduced public probation sector the national centre will have to deal with any contract failure.    </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">A less risky</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> more effective</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> approach</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, that made better use of scarce resources,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> would be to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">give urgent priority</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to “through the gate” services for ex-prisoners, particularly for those sentenced to less than 12 months</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> while continuing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">reform of the public sector probation service.  Th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e latter</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> would be in line with Government policy in relation to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">custody</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">it</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">recently </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">cancelled part of its proposed competition for prisons because it was satisfied HM Prison Service had </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">developed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> a satisfactory </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">new </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">delivery model that could be implemented without needing to test it against other providers’ proposals.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Developing post-release services for ex-prisoners</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">There are two principle options to extend post-release supervision to the “under 12 months” category of prisoners.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Extend statutory supervision by probation services to this group.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This would have the advantage of ensuring every ex-prisoner was supervised.  However, resources would have to be spread thinly across not only offenders who would be likely to respond well to supervision but also those who were unresponsive and challenging, i.e. those who would reoffend </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">whatever the help available</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  There would be costs for probation providers </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and others such as prisons and the Parole Board </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in relation to the administration of the licences and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">breach and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">recall.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Extend voluntary supervision by any provider to this group.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">R</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">esources would be invested where they were most likely to have a positive effect</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> on those who were</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">with help </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">motivated </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">able </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to change.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> There would be many possible models, including the current PbR pilots, and the Government could test various approaches.  This would not preclude moving to a mandatory system in due course. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> It is the more flexible </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and value-for-money </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">option.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Probation trusts should not be excluded from running such schemes.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Further reform of public sector probation</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Probation is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">successful</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> public service:</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Probation trust board members were selected explicitly because they have the skills to lead competitive, business-like organisations.   </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">All probation boards in England and Wales had to meet enhanced performance standards, including for efficiency, in order to achieve their current trust status.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">All trusts currently meet or exceed performance standards set by Government.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Probation trusts collectively won the 2011 British Quality Foundation’s 2011 Gold Medal for Excellence, the first public sector organisation to do so.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The England and Wales probation service </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">is well-regarded internationally</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  The Ministry of Justice </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">has</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> an International Projects Team that provides a consultancy service to the many countries around the world that wish to develop their probation services along English </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">/</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Welsh lines.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">To </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">enhance its effectiveness</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the Government </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">could</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> introduce</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">:</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Outcome </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">based</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> contracts between the Secretary of State and trusts</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">include a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">clear pricing structure and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">financial rewards / penalties</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> drive trusts to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">perform better and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">seek the most cost-effective provider.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">A “line management” culture would have to be eliminated from the relationship between NOMS and trusts with both parties adapt</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> their approach</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to become more, literally, business-like</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">A </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">contractual </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">requirement to compete </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">any</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> aspect</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of probation services</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> as required</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, other than </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">advice to courts</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">he probation profession has said that offender management should </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">also </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">be reserved to public sector probation but this is unnecessarily restrictive</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Public sector probation would continue to hold (i.e. be responsible for) all orders and licences but offender management and/or day-to-day supervision could be undertaken by a variety of providers.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Trusts would be able to compete to provide services to their own and/or other trusts.  Trusts would be free to commission alone, in consortia of trusts or on a co-commissioning basis depending on the nature of the services sought.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  Arrangements would need to be introduced to regulate the commissioning process.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">A stripping out of unnecessary bureaucracy and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">mandatory </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">process</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">es</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">matched by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">explicit </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">encouragement to innovate. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">A development programme for trusts as commissioners and contract managers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> so that they could manage</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> large scale commissioning </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> contract management of core services</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> co-commissioning across large geographical </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">areas</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> manag</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> contracts that contain </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">significant </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">financial reward and penalty clauses</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  </span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rusts would have to accept, and support, that:</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Secretary of State</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> could rule that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">trusts must put out any of their functions to competition</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  As a result</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">trust might no longer </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">deliver</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">one or more</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">front-line service</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s itself</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> although </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">it</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> would retain overall control as the commissioner</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">service</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, the contract manager</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">as </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">holder of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the relevant </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">orders and licences</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  </span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Staff might have to be seconded or TUPE-transferred to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">an organisation that won a contract</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Redundancies or renegotiated terms and conditions of employment in pursuit of efficiency would remain </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">possib</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ility</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li st